Sainsbury wants to break through in the British beauty market
Sainsbury's competes with Boots, Superdrug and Debenhams and directs beauty departments where specialist assistants work, such as in wholesale stores.
The initiative is part of a strategy to conquer the British beauty market, which is worth £2.8 billion and continues to grow, while the sale of fashion and household items continues to decline. The larger beauty wards are tested in 11 stores across the country. If they turn out to be a success, they will be introduced into even more stores next year.
The investment in the beauty market is also a result of the fact that supermarkets want to fill the shelves where TVs, microwaves and interior items once stood, with other products.
Sainsbury's wants to double its beauty offer and offer 3,000 products, including for the first time brands such as Revlon, Essie, Tweezerman and Dr. PawPaw.
The existing range of L'Oreal, Maybelline and Burt's Bees is also given more space, with display space per brand, as in shops like Boots.
The supermarket also re-markets its Boutique make-up, now that most products are suitable for vegans, something younger shoppers increasingly demand.
In addition, perfumery will award the Fragrance Shop in two shops of Sainsbury's. The first was opened in Croydon, in southern London, the second is opened later this year in Selly Oak, in Birmingham.
Because more and more people shop online and increasingly buy small amounts of food on a daily basis in local supermarkets, supermarkets need to make more effort to convince people to shop with them.
Mike Coupe, Chief Executive of Sainsbury's, says the stores will look more and more like wholesale stores, as the supermarket chain competes against discounters Aldi and Lidl, with more services and non-food.
Sainsbury's has integrated Argos sales points into hundreds of stores and has also opened a number of Habitats since both chains were taken over two years ago. According to the company, the sale of food has increased and the acquisitions have yielded more returns.
The last time the supermarket tried to give its departments Beauty and Pharmacy a makeover, that became a flop.
Sainsbury's tested a collaboration with Boots in the early 2000s, but the collaboration was ended when a conflict arose over the distribution of income from the pharmacy department in the supermarkets.
This is a new strategy since Sainsbury's 281 pharmacy departments in stores sold to Celesio, owner of the Lloyds Pharmacy chain three years ago for a sum of £ 125 million.
Lloyds would also play a role in the plan, adding an extensive range of luxury brands for skin care, including La Roche-Posay and Vichy, in four stores.
Paul Mills-Hicks, Commercial Director of Sainsbury's, said: ‘We have completely changed the decor of our beauty department, so that it is more pleasant for our customers.
We have also invested in the specialized training of our employees, who will be ready to give advice.
With our range of brands, we offer something for everyone, and thanks to the attractive environment and convenient locations, we ensure that our customers like to buy their beauty products from us, and no longer shop in the old way.'
