Throughout the country-circled Bolivia, the memory of the coastline that the country had to give up to Chile after a bloody nineteenth-century conflict of raw materials has still been vivid, as has the desire to revade the Pacific.
That hope may have reached its highest point in recent decades, as Bolivia is waiting for a ruling from the International Court of Justice, which should fall on 1 October after five years of debate.
‘Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and naturally looks forward to the result with positive prospects', said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians across the country will look at the court's ruling on large screens, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will argue in favour of Bolivia that Chile, after decades of tough talks, is obliged to give Bolivia a sovereign access to the sea.
