‘We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,’ he swore at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court will probably not decide in favor of Bolivia, and even if it did, little would change.
The UN body based in the Netherlands does not have the authority to grant Chilean territory and has indicated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the ruling of the International Court of Justice falls only six months after the final statements indicates that the case was ‘not complicated', says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And the prospects for a positive outcome of Bolivia have certainly not improved, on the contrary, in the last four years the situation has perhaps even worsened.
‘The matter surrounding access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian government,’ Zárate said.
The warlike rhetoric of Morales has completely undermined all the goodwill that Chile might still have undermined, she claimed.
Bolivia and Chile will continue their talks at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to continue talking after.
The two countries have not had an ambassador to each other since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, representing Bolivia in The Hague, denies that the court's decision has been taken unusually quickly.
On Monday, Bolivia will ‘have an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of international relations with Chile' and an opportunity to ‘put an end to 139 years of disagreements, with mutual benefits', he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents of Latin America, uses the maritime issue as a political crutch.
