John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have an excellent record of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with yet another set of excellent exam results, as well as individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other initiatives of the whole community.
With over 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for secondary and higher education, their chosen career and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desirable subjects par excellence within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: ‘If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
When you talk to him in his own language, you reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and a relationship of trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam results, we can conclude that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students studying foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated to SCIS, shows that 72 percent of students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students German, 69 percent of students French and 63 percent of students Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now as much valued as trade choice as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A study by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that of the stumbling blocks to fill job vacancies, 17% were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Language skills are thus becoming increasingly important for preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job vacancies require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he has a real advantage in the future with such skill for life.
Direct communication with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person a competitive edge.
According to a YouGov poll among more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation. French was the only language to exceed 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today's children.
Speaking several languages, particularly those of emerging economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK when they look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot be denied at present that languages remain vital to the future of the country in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be regarded as 'international communication skills'.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
