Harvard students attend courses on the importance of sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night and drink a lot of caffeine.
A professor noted that the students of the world's largest university often have no idea of the basic principles of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course. As far as he knows, it is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech on the influence of sleep deprivation on learning.
'At the end of my speech, a girl came to me saying, 'Why did I only hear this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is organized for the first time this year, explains to the students the basic principles of how good sleeping habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was established that students had a serious sleep deprivation during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the parts, students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a routine when going to sleep.
In another section, participants are told how long - term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a map of the campus, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine.
‘We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we feel that they have the right to know all this, just as people have the right to know the consequences of choosing cigarettes on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride on a night of study still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and increasing pressure on students sleep deprivation is an increasing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep, of good quality, must be the student's ‘secret weapon' to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to prepare the course, after which he had attended the professor's class last year when he studied at Harvard in his first year.
He said the course had opened its eyes and inspired him to ensure that the course became available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before they come to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, not just an alarm to stand up. They also need to be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronics screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, which can make you have trouble falling asleep.
