HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% new cases
China reports that the number of Chinese with HIV and AIDS has increased by 14%.
Health authorities say that over 820,000 people have been affected in the country.
40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
In the vast majority of new cases, the diseases were passed on through sex, which was not previously so.
In the past, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China through transfusions of contaminated blood.
But the number of people suffering from HIV in this way is now almost zero, said Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, compared to the same period last year, the number of people with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
The transmission of HIV through sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has no longer been punishable in China since 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is reported to be widespread.
According to studies, due to the conservative values of land, an estimated 70 to 90% of men having sex with men would eventually marry a woman.
Often the diseases are transmitted by inadequate protection in sexual relations in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication as part of efforts to address the problem.
