What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it contributed to reducing poverty?
This Saturday the Global Citizen Festival will be held in New York, an annual music event where a very impressive line-up of stars will perform and which has an equally impressive mission: the end of poverty in the world.
For the seventh time again, tens of thousands of people will come to the Great Lawn in Central Park for the Global Citizens Festival. Not only to enjoy acts like Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes but also to raise awareness for the real goal: ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which was first organised in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a group of international advocators who hope to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting against it.
Concertgoers who want to obtain a free ticket for the event (unless they were willing to pay for a VIP ticket), had to complete a series of tasks, or 'actions', such as volunteering, e-mail a world leader, make a phone call or generate awareness for the goal in another meaningful way: an end to poverty.
But how successful has the Global Citizen Festival been, with 12 more years to go to achieve this goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a suitable way to convince people to demand a call for action or is this just another form of 'click ivism', making people feel that they are making a real contribution by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, according to Global Citizens, more than 19 million 'actions' of supporters have been registered, aimed at a large number of different targets.
According to Global Citizens, these actions have contributed to the commitment of world leaders and to policy proposals worth more than $37 billion to change the lives of 2.25 billion people by 2030.
Early in 2018, the group cited 390 initiatives and statements based on the actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been paid or brought together by sponsorship actions.
The group estimates that the funds obtained so far have had an impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
Among the main declarations of intent are those of The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of investors and executives from the United Kingdom with the aim of 'helping children realise their full potential'. This group has promised $35 million to help Rwanda end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the help of the British government, of donors, of other national governments and of Global Citizens like you, we can make the social injustice that is malnutrition a footnote in history," Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, told the audience at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also announced that, after more than 5,000 actions were sent asking the British government to improve the nutritional situation for mothers and children, the government has announced support for a project, the Power of Nutrition, which will reach 5 million women and children with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the Global Citizens website that was asked "why do you think we can put an end to extreme poverty?"
the group replied, "It will be a long and difficult road, sometimes falling and failing.
But, like civil rights and the anti-apartheid movements ahead of us, we will eventually be successful because we are stronger together.
