Germany's new warship postponed again
The latest frigate of the German Navy should have come into service in 2014, replacing the obsolete warships of the Cold War time, but it will take at least one more year before it is ready, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the 'Rheinland-Pfalz', the leading ship in the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit that quotes a military spokesman.
The vessel should have been part of the Navy in 2014, but the disturbing problems after delivery have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four vessels of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 are intended to replace the obsolete frigates of the Bremen class.
As far as we know, they have a powerful cannon, a series of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles and a form of stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic characteristics.
Other important features include longer maintenance cycles, it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates up to two years in a row, far away from home ports.
However, the ongoing delays mean that the advanced warships, which are intended to allow Germany to project its power overseas, are already obsolete by the time they are put into operation, notes Die Zeit.
The fateful frigate F125 made all the headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy has sent a ship back to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons behind this return, but German media cited a number of crucial 'software and hardware defects' that would render the warship useless if it were deployed in a combat mission.
Software defects were especially important because the boats of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class are served by a crew of about 120 seamen, half the manpower on the frigates of the older Bremen class.
It also became clear that the ship is suffering from a severe overweight, which will reduce performance and limit the capabilities of the Navy to perform further upgrades.
The 'Rheinland-Pfalz' weighs 7,000 tons, which is twice as much as ships of a similar class used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the price tag for the entire project, including the training of the crew, is also a problem.
It is said that this has reached a staggering €3.1 billion compared to the original €2.2 billion.
The problems that the latest frigates have in their grip are becoming extra important because of the recent warnings that the power of the German Navy is decreasing.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the Parliamentary Defence Commission in Germany, acknowledged that the Navy is in fact "a shortage of deployable ships".
