National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on an estate in the Scottish highlands, attempts to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study conducted by scientists of the National Trust for Scotland follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown large-eared bat and the water bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to track the activities of the bats throughout the season.
Staff of the NTS and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations using hand detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the cries of the bat and what kind does what.
A map of the habitat and a report is then produced to create a detailed picture on a landscape scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor to the NTS, hopes that the results show which habitat areas are the most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making meadows and how we can best maintain forests for bats and similar species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities affecting berths and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightnings can also pose a risk, as can fly traps and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits make their ears more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use an advanced echo location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight route.
At the NTS, which is responsible for caring for over 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 acres ashore in the country, bats are taken very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who carry out regular surveys, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even set up the first and only reserve for bats in Scotland at the Threeave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland's ten species of bats live.
Landscape manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for the bats.
"Here in Threeave we have a great environment for bats" he said.
"We have the old buildings, many very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much about bats is not yet known and that is why the work we do here and at other locations will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
He stresses the importance of monitoring bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place can lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, possibly eliminating a full local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or to destroy their sleeping accommodations.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to make a contribution to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and of many of our species we simply don't know how their populations are doing."
