He went to the Stadium of Light last summer after returning St Mirren to the Scottish Premiership the previous season.
"As a football player, I wanted to play for my country.
But I was selected for the B-team and with that the stocking was finished" Ross told Sportsound on BBC Scotland.
"When I was a child I saw Scotland play often with my father in Hampden Park and it's something that keeps on attracting me.
However, that possibility would not come until I am successful in managing a club."
Ross' predecessors as managers of Sunderland include Dick Lawyer, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former boss of Alloa Athletic says he was not intimidated to become the successor of these established names at a major club, previously he had refused advances by Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Success for me is currently measured by 'can I have this club returned to the Premier League?'
Due to its structure and facilities at this club, it should undoubtedly be in the Premier League," he says.
"It's not an easy task to achieve this, but I can't see myself as successful until I bring the club back there."
Ross is only three years into his career as manager, after a period as assistant manager at Dumbarton and 15 months into Hearts' coaching group.
He then helped Alloa recover from relegation to the third division and has transformed St Mirren from on the edge of relegation to winning the Championship in the next season.
And Ross says he now feels more comfortable than he ever did during his career as a footballer with Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
"It was probably really a crossroads" he remembered from the moment he took charge at Alloa.
"I really believed that management was the right choice for me, much more than playing.
It sounds bizarre, because I was doing pretty well, I earned pretty well and I had some reasonable highlights.
But playing football can be tough.
There are a lot of things you're confronted with weekly.
I still have that, given the stress and the pressure of the profession, but management just feels good.
I've always wanted to be a manager and now that I'm real, I'm as good in my skin as I've never felt in my adult life."
