At least 384 people have been killed by a powerful earthquake and a tsunami that has hit the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, officials said, and the death toll is expected to rise further.
As the means of communication have been disabled, the official agencies have not yet received information from the Donggala Regency, an area north of Palu that is closer to the epicenter of the quake with a force of 7.5 on the Richter scale.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people have been evacuated after the disaster occurred.
Here are some important facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Celebes:
Palu is the capital of the province of Central Celebes and is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Celebes, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated its 40th birthday when the tsunami struck.
Donggala is a regency that extends over 300 km along the coast of northwest Celebes.
The regency, an administrative region just under a province, had an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main activities in the economy of the province of Central Celebes, especially in the coastal area of Donggala.
Nickel mines are also important in the province, but they are mostly located in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have been regularly affected by tsunamis over the past 100 years, according to the Agency for Combating Disasters of Indonesia.
In 1938, a tsunami claimed over 200 lives and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck in western Donggala in 1996, with nine deaths.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific Ring of Fire and is often affected by earthquakes.
Here is a list of some of the most severe earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh on north Sumatra on 26 December caused a tsunami that affected 14 countries and claimed a total of 226,000 lives along the coasts of the Indian Ocean, more than half of it in Aceh.
2005: A series of severe earthquakes occurred on the west coast of Sumatra at the end of March and early April.
Hundreds of people were killed on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake with a power of 6.8 on the Richter scale occurred south of Java, Indonesia's most densely populated island, causing a tsunami that struck on the south coast and claimed nearly 700 lives.
2009: An earthquake with a force of 7.6 on the Richter scale hit the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake with a force of 7.5 on the Richter scale hit one of the Mentawai Islands, off the coast of Sumatra, and caused a tsunami of over 10 metres that destroyed dozens of villages and demanded around 300 human lives.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the Pidie regency in Aceh and caused destruction and panic, as the people were reminded of the destructions of the 2004 deadly earthquake and tsunami.
There was no tsunami this time but more than 100 people found death due to crashing buildings.
2018: Several earthquakes hit the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the north side of the island.
